description:
What: lichen_pubkey_to_iid() declares hash[32] on stack, calls lichen_sha256(), and if that fails, goes to cleanup which zeros hash. But if lichen_sha256 returns an error, hash may be uninitialized (never written to).

Why it matters: The cleanup path calls secure_zero(hash, sizeof(hash)) regardless of whether hash was written. This is actually SAFE - zeroing uninitialized memory is well-defined. The concern is if the compiler optimizes away the zero because hash was never 'used'.

The volatile access in secure_zero() should prevent this optimization. Not a bug.

Evidence:
```c
uint8_t hash[TC_SHA256_DIGEST_SIZE];  // uninitialized
ret = lichen_sha256(pubkey, LICHEN_ED25519_PUBKEY_LEN, hash);
if (ret != 0) {
    LOG_ERR(...);
    goto cleanup;  // hash may be uninitialized here
}
// ...
cleanup:
    secure_zero(hash, sizeof(hash));  // zeros possibly-uninitialized buffer - OK
```
